================================================================================
 WHY MESSAGING? -- THE CORE PROBLEM
================================================================================
  OLD WAY -- TIGHT COUPLING (HTTP Sync)
  --------------------------------------

  +------------+   HTTP call   +-------------+   HTTP call   +------------+
  | Order Svc  | ------------> | Payment Svc | ------------> | Email Svc  |
  +------------+               +-------------+               +------------+

  Problems:
  - Payment slow    --> Order waits (latency cascades)
  - Payment down    --> Order fails (failure cascades)
  - High traffic    --> All services must scale together
  - No retry        --> Lost requests on failure
  - Tight coupling  --> Cannot deploy independently


  NEW WAY -- LOOSE COUPLING (Messaging)
  ---------------------------------------
  +------------+  publish  +-------------------+  consume  +-------------+
  | Order Svc  | --------> |   Message Broker  | --------> | Payment Svc |
  +------------+           |  (Kafka/Rabbit/   |           +-------------+
                           |   Azure Svc Bus)  |  consume  +-------------+
                           |                   | --------> |  Email Svc  |
                           +-------------------+           +-------------+

  Benefits:
  - Order never waits            (async, fire and forget)
  - Payment can be down          (broker holds message)
  - Scale independently          (each service scales alone)
  - Automatic retry              (broker retries on failure)
  - Multiple consumers           (one event -> many handlers)
  - Replay messages              (Kafka only)
  - Decouple deployment          (release independently)


================================================================================
 EVOLUTION OF MESSAGING IN JAVA / SPRING
================================================================================
  Generation 1: JMS (Java Message Service) -- 2001
  --------------------------------------------------
  - Standard Java API for messaging
  - Works with ActiveMQ, IBM MQ, WebSphere MQ
  - Point-to-point (Queue) and Pub/Sub (Topic)
  - Synchronous, heavyweight, XML-heavy config
  - Used in: EJB / J2EE enterprise applications

  Generation 2: Spring JMS -- 2004
  ----------------------------------
  - Wraps JMS API with Spring simplicity
  - JmsTemplate, @JmsListener
  - Still relies on JMS-compliant broker (ActiveMQ etc.)
  - Less boilerplate than raw JMS

  Generation 3: RabbitMQ + Spring AMQP -- 2010
  ----------------------------------------------
  - AMQP protocol (not JMS)
  - Smart routing via Exchanges
  - Better than JMS: flexible routing, dead letter queues
  - Spring AMQP / Spring Cloud Stream

  Generation 4: Apache Kafka + Spring Kafka -- 2014
  ---------------------------------------------------
  - Log-based, not queue-based
  - Millions of messages/second
  - Replay, time-travel, event sourcing
  - Spring Kafka / Spring Cloud Stream

  Generation 5: Cloud-native (Azure Service Bus, SQS, Pub/Sub)
  --------------------------------------------------------------
  - Fully managed, no infra to run
  - Pay per use, auto-scale
  - Azure Service Bus: enterprise JMS 2.0 support
  - Spring Cloud Azure integration

  Why move from JMS to Kafka/Rabbit?
  -----------------------------------
  JMS Problem                    Modern Solution
  ------------------------------ ---------------------------
  Broker is single point failure Kafka: distributed cluster
  Slow (thousands/sec)           Kafka: millions/sec
  No message replay              Kafka: log retention
  Complex XML config             Spring annotations
  No cloud-native option         Azure Service Bus, SQS
  Poor horizontal scaling        Kafka partitions


