1. Understanding Partitions
    Before looking at the strategies, you have to understand the destination.
    A Topic in Kafka is divided into multiple Partitions.
Parallelism: Each partition can be hosted on a different server (Broker), allowing Kafka to scale.
Order: Kafka only guarantees the order of messages within a single partition, not across the whole topic.

Partitioning Strategy (Key-Based):
    This is the "intelligent" way to route data. 
    When you send a message with a Key (e.g., customer_id or order_id), Kafka uses a partitioner to hash that key.
    How it works: partition=hash(key)(modnum_partitions)
    The Result: All messages with the same key will always go to the same partition.
    Why use it? This is crucial for Stateful Processing.
    If you are calculating a bank balance, you need all transactions for "Customer A" to arrive in the same order at the same consumer.

Round Robin Strategy (No Key):
    If you send a message without a key (null key), Kafka's default behavior is to distribute messages evenly across all available partitions.
    How it works: Message 1 goes to Partition 0, Message 2 to Partition 1, Message 3 to Partition 2, and so on.
    The Result: An even "smear" of data across the entire cluster.
    Why use it? It provides maximum load balancing.
    No single broker gets overwhelmed while others sit idle.
    It is perfect for stateless data where the order relative to other messages doesn't matter (e.g., simple logging).

Sticky Partitioner (The 2026 Context):
    In modern Kafka versions (and certainly by 2026), the "Round Robin" logic has been optimized into the Sticky Partitioner.
    Instead of jumping partitions for every single message (which is inefficient for network batching),
    Kafka "sticks" to one partition for a small batch of messages before moving to the next.
    This significantly reduces latency and CPU usage while still achieving a balanced distribution over time.

Note: If you find that one partition is much larger than others (a "Hot Partition"),
it usually means your Partitioning Key isn't diverse enough (e.g., partitioning by Country when 90% of your users are from one country).

