 PART 5: ADVANCED PATTERNS
================================================================================
  PATTERN 1: SAGA PATTERN (Distributed Transactions)
  ----------------------------------------------------

  Problem: Order service and Payment service need to either BOTH
           succeed or BOTH fail, but they are separate services.

  Solution: Saga - a sequence of local transactions with compensating
            transactions on failure.

  CHOREOGRAPHY SAGA (event-driven):
  ----------------------------------

  Order Svc         Kafka            Payment Svc      Inventory Svc
  ---------         -----            -----------      -------------
  place order
       |
       | publish "order.created"
       +----------->
                    |
                    | consume "order.created"
                    +-------------------->
                                     process payment
                                          |
                                          | publish "payment.success"
                                          +-------->
                                                   consume "payment.success"
                                                   reserve inventory
                                                          |
                                                          | publish "inventory.reserved"
                                                          +-------->
                                                   Order Svc consumes
                                                   --> order CONFIRMED

  Failure:
  Payment fails --> publish "payment.failed"
  Order Svc consumes --> publish "order.cancelled" (compensate)


  PATTERN 2: OUTBOX PATTERN (Guaranteed Delivery)
  ------------------------------------------------
  Problem: Service saves to DB and publishes event.
           What if publish fails after DB save?
           --> DB updated but event never sent.

  Solution: Write event to OUTBOX table in same DB transaction.
            Separate poller reads outbox and publishes to broker.

  OrderService                DB               Kafka
  ------------                --               -----
  @Transactional
  placeOrder():
       |
       | INSERT orders (order data)         +-----------+
       |-----------------------------------> | orders    |
       |                                    +-----------+
       | INSERT outbox (event data)
       |-----------------------------------> +-----------+
       |                                    | outbox    |
       v                                    +-----------+
  transaction committed                          |
                                                 | Outbox Poller (every 1s)
                                                 | reads unpublished rows
                                                 |
                                                 +-----> publish to Kafka
                                                         mark as published


  PATTERN 3: COMPETING CONSUMERS (Load Balancing)
  -------------------------------------------------
  Queue: order-queue
  [msg1][msg2][msg3][msg4][msg5][msg6]

  Consumer Instance 1: picks msg1, msg4  (processes in parallel)
  Consumer Instance 2: picks msg2, msg5
  Consumer Instance 3: picks msg3, msg6

  --> Scale consumers horizontally to handle more load
  --> Kafka: add more partitions + consumers in same group
  

  PATTERN 4: MESSAGE FILTERING (Content-Based Routing)
  ------------------------------------------------------
  One topic, different consumers for different message types:
  Kafka:
  @KafkaListener(topics = "order-events",
    filter = "orderTypeFilter")   // Spring bean that returns true/false
  public void handleVIPOrders(OrderEvent event) { ... }

  @Bean
  public RecordFilterStrategy<String, OrderEvent> orderTypeFilter() {
      return record -> !record.value().getCustomerType().equals("VIP");
      // return true = skip (filter out), false = process
  }

  RabbitMQ: Use topic routing key patterns or headers exchange.
  Azure SB: Use subscription SQL filter expressions.

  PATTERN 5: REQUEST-REPLY (Sync over Async)
  -------------------------------------------
  Sometimes you need a response from async messaging.

  Requestor                   Broker              Responder
  ---------                   ------              ---------
  create replyTo queue: "reply-queue-xyz"
       |
       | publish to "order-request-queue"
       | header: replyTo = "reply-queue-xyz"
       | header: correlationId = "abc123"
       +------------------------------>
                                       consume "order-request-queue"
                                       process request
                                            |
                                            | publish to "reply-queue-xyz"
                                            | header: correlationId="abc123"
                                            +--------->
       |
       | receive from "reply-queue-xyz"
       | match correlationId = "abc123"
       | <------------------------------
  got response!
  // Spring RabbitMQ built-in support:
  Object response = rabbitTemplate.convertSendAndReceive(
      "order-exchange", "order.request", requestEvent);

