 PART 9: IDEMPOTENCY (PROCESS MESSAGE EXACTLY ONCE)
================================================================================
  Problem: Consumer processes message, crashes BEFORE acking.
  Broker redelivers. Message processed TWICE.
  --> Duplicate payment, duplicate email, etc.

  Solution: Idempotency key (eventId)

  @Service
  public class PaymentConsumer {
      @Autowired
      private ProcessedEventRepository processedEvents;
      @KafkaListener(topics = "order-events")
      public void handle(OrderEvent event, Acknowledgment ack) {
          // Check if already processed
          if (processedEvents.existsByEventId(event.getEventId())) {
              log.warn("Duplicate event {}, skipping", event.getEventId());
              ack.acknowledge();  // ack to prevent re-delivery
              return;
          }

          // Process in transaction with idempotency record
          processedEvents.save(new ProcessedEvent(event.getEventId()));
          paymentService.charge(event);
          ack.acknowledge();
      }
  }

  @Entity
  public class ProcessedEvent {
      @Id
      private String eventId;    // UUID from message envelope
      private Instant processedAt;
  }


================================================================================
 COMPARISON: WHEN TO USE WHICH BROKER
================================================================================
  USE KAFKA WHEN:
  ---------------
  - You need very high throughput (millions of msgs/sec)
  - You need message replay / event sourcing
  - You are building event-driven microservices at scale
  - You need stream processing (Kafka Streams / Flink)
  - You want a distributed commit log
  - Example: user activity tracking, financial transactions,
             IoT data ingestion, audit logs

  USE RABBITMQ WHEN:
  ------------------
  - You need complex routing (multiple exchange types)
  - You need task queues (background jobs, work distribution)
  - You need request-reply patterns
  - You want simpler setup than Kafka
  - Message ordering is NOT critical
  - Example: email sending, report generation, task scheduling

  USE AZURE SERVICE BUS WHEN:
  ---------------------------
  - You are on Azure and want fully managed messaging
  - You need guaranteed message ordering (sessions)
  - You need enterprise features (transactions, dedup)
  - You use JMS 2.0 standard API
  - You want to avoid managing broker infrastructure
  - Example: enterprise Azure workloads, lift-and-shift from
             JMS/ActiveMQ, government/regulated workloads


