AMQP:
AMQP plays a key role when working with cloud messaging systems like Azure Service Bus. Let’s break it down simply and practically 👇

🔹 What is AMQP?
   Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) is an open standard protocol used for message-oriented middleware.
👉 In simple terms:
   It defines how messages are sent, received, and acknowledged
   Works over TCP (usually port 5672 / 5671 for TLS)
   Ensures reliable, secure, and asynchronous communication
🔸 AMQP in Azure Service Bus
   **Azure Service Bus uses AMQP as its primary protocol for communication between clients and the broker.
✅ Why AMQP is used
   Reliable delivery (no message loss)
   Supports queue + topic (pub/sub)
   Efficient for high-throughput systems
   Supports transactions and batching
🔧 How it works (Flow)
      Producer sends message using AMQP
      Service Bus receives and stores it
      Consumer receives message via AMQP
      Consumer acknowledges (complete) or abandons/retries
📦 Key AMQP Concepts in Service Bus
   1. Connections & Sessions
      A TCP connection is established
      Multiple sessions (channels) can run inside one connection
   2. Links
      Logical communication paths
      Sender link → send messages
      Receiver link → receive messages
   3. Settlement (Very Important)
      Defines what happens after receiving a message:
      Complete → message removed
      Abandon → message available again
      Dead-letter → moved to DLQ
      Defer → postpone processing

| Feature     | AMQP                | HTTP             |
| ----------- | ------------------- | ---------------- |
| Performance | High                | Lower            |
| Connection  | Persistent          | Request/Response |
| Latency     | Low                 | Higher           |
| Use case    | Real-time messaging | Simple APIs      |

🚀 Real-World Usage
   Microservices communication
   Event-driven architecture
   Order processing systems
   Banking / financial messaging

🔥 Example (Java - Service Bus using AMQP)
   Using Azure SDK (internally uses AMQP):
   ServiceBusSenderClient sender = new ServiceBusClientBuilder()
       .connectionString("<connection-string>")
       .sender()
       .queueName("orders")
       .buildClient();
   sender.sendMessage(new ServiceBusMessage("Order created"));
   
   👉 Even though you don’t see AMQP explicitly, the SDK uses it under the hood.
